- I've tried inspecting the `parameters` object inside `EtherscanService#verifyContract` and the given API key is correct.

Thank you. Also, great work! This package made my life a lot easier.

@alcuadrado Thanks for getting back to me. I've tried testing this [GET request](https://docs.bscscan.com/api-endpoints/tokens#get-bep-20-token-totalsupply-by-contractaddress) to try isolating the problem:
- Using curl: It returned the expected response
- Using [got](https://www.npmjs.com/package/got) package: It returned the expected response.

```
const response = await got("https://api-testnet.bscscan.com/api....");
console.log(response.body);
=> {"status":"1","message":"OK","result":"1000000000000000000000000000"}
```

- Replacing the `fetch` code inside `dist/src/EtherscanService.js` with the following code:

```
const res = await fetch("https://api-testnet.bscscan.com/api....");
console.log(await res.text());
```

It returned a similar response in my original post. So I wondered if there's any issue with the `node-fetch` package, so I created a separated script to test it:

```
async function main() {
  const res = await fetch(
    "https://api-testnet.bscscan.com/api...."
  );
  console.log(await res.text());
}
```

And indeed, the request got blocked by Cloudflare just like the verification task. It's strange because it still worked perfectly yesterday.

I hope this can help :)
